sections:
  0. masthead         [36mcinematic[0m/lg  A quiet title card: the knife's name, the smith's name, and the claim that it is made to outlive its owner — nothing else.
  1. the-ore          [36meditorial[0m/md  Origin: where the carbon steel billet comes from and why this smith chose it — establishing credibility before any claim is made.
  2. day-one-fire     [36mnarrative[0m/lg  Forging: the billet heated and hammered into rough shape — the first of four days, establishing the timeline's pace.
  3. day-two-three-patience [36mtimeline[0m/xl  Grinding, quenching, tempering — the unglamorous middle days where most of the time and risk lives, told as a vertical sequence to earn the four-day claim.
  4. day-four-the-edge [36masymmetric[0m/xl  Final sharpening and the smith's signature stamp — the single moment isolated as the emotional anchor of the whole page.
  5. why-it-outlives-you [36meditorial[0m/md  The thesis: carbon steel patinas and can be reforged, resharpened, passed down — this is not a consumable object, it is inherited.
  6. the-smith        [36masymmetric[0m/md  Proof through person: one paragraph on the maker in Sheffield, grounding the whole story in a named individual rather than a brand.
  7. acquire          [36meditorial[0m/sm  The single, quiet call to action: reserve a knife from the current batch, with the wait understood as part of the value.
  8. close            [36meditorial[0m/md  land the ending; a story that stops is not a story that closes

